ally increased industrialization. Led by a group of “merchant kings” who exemplified gentlemanly capitalism, this ambitious trading project transformed the small, economically moribund Netherlands into a global power. Merchant Kings offers a fascinating interdisciplinary exploration of this episode and reveals not only the distinctive nature of the Dutch state, but the surprising extent to which its nascent corporate innovations were rooted in early welfare initiatives. By placing colony and metropole into a single analytical frame, this book offers a bracing new approach to understanding the development of modern corporations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aColonial companieszIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCorporations, DutchxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aCorporations, DutchxPolitical aspectszIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCorporatizationzNetherlandsxHistoryy19th century. 70(DE-588)4026651-50(DE-627)1062874270(DE-576)208967435aImperialismus2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311099767540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800730519?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800730519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800730519/original  a978-3-11-099767-5  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK